{"cursor":"9911","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Bureau of Labor Statistics |logo =\nBureau of labor statistics logo.svg |logo_width = 200px |formed = 1884\n|preceding1 = |jurisdiction = Federal government of the United States\n|headquarters = Postal Square Building Washington, D.C. |employees =\n2,500 |budget = $618.2 million \n\n\n|chief1_name = Erica Groshen\n\n|chief1_position = Commissioner \n\n|chief2_name = John M. (Jack) Galvin \n\n|chief2_position = Deputy Commissioner \n\n|chief3_name = |chief3_position = |child1_agency = |website =\n[http://www.bls.gov/ www.bls.gov]  [http://www.dol.gov/bls www.dol.gov/bls]\n|footnotes = }} {{Multiple issues\n| primarysources = May 2011 refimprove = September 2010\n}} The 'Bureau of Labor Statistics' ('BLS') is a unit of the United States\nDepartment of Labor. It is the principal fact-finding agency for the U.S.\ngovernment in the broad field of labor economics and statistics and serves as a\nprincipal agency of the U.S. Federal Statistical System. The BLS is a\ngovernmental statistical agency that collects, processes, analyzes, and\ndisseminates essential statistical data to the American public, the U.S.\nCongress, other Federal agencies, State and local governments, business, and\nlabor representatives. The BLS also serves as a statistical resource to the\nDepartment of Labor.\n\nThe BLS data must satisfy a number of criteria, including relevance to current\nsocial and economic issues, timeliness in reflecting todayâs rapidly changing\neconomic conditions, accuracy and consistently high statistical quality, and\nimpartiality in both subject matter and presentation. To avoid the appearance of\npartiality, the dates of major data releases are scheduled more than a year in\nadvance, in coordination with the Office of Management and Budget.\n","linknr":299,"url":"Bureau_of_Labor_Statistics","recorded":1376421102,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bureau_of_Labor_Stat